Couples who violate politics face huge fines, up to three times their annual salary in some areas, and labour discrimination.
Chinese officials have misused the policy for their contribution to avoid critical pressure on their natural resources, while human rights defenders have reported abuses in the imposition of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women with a second child to undergo abortions.
In addition, many couples have had abortions according to the sex of the fetus, leading to a high unnatural male-female proportion.
In recent years, demographic officials have gradually abandoned their position on the policy of a single child.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule, including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which both husband and wife are single children, and in 2007 many of their hardline slogans were eased.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor of the Institute for Demographic Research at the University of Beijing, said that central government officials have recently been discussing even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the spouses is a single child.
In July Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost evening morning, the posters that ordered families to have one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who would be suitable for having a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city's government sent family and volunteer planning officers to visit couples in their homes and slide leaflets under the doors.
It has also promised to provide emotional and financial guidance to those who have chosen to have more than one child.
Family planning officials say the response has been very little overwhelming.
Disabling Response
Although the officials of a rural city outside Shanghai said they observed a moderate increase in the requests of couples who wanted a second child after the campaign was launched, the most urban districts did not indicate any change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, is still receiving only four to five applications a month.
The disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to reach only about 165,000, slightly more than in 2009, but less than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Caolu municipality family planning committee in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason many people don't want any more children.
They want to give their first son the best, he said.
Yang Jiawei, 27 years old, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and are legally enabled to do so.
But like many Chinese, they only have insufficient medical and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social protection network, they maintain, that option would be irresponsible.
People in the West wrongly view single child policy as a matter of rights, Yang said, a construction engineer whose wife is pregnant for seven months from the first child of the couple.
Yeah, we're stealing the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just a political issue.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their doubts.
Wang, the human resources manager, said he wanted a single child because she was also: "We were the center of our families and we were used to everyone taking care of us.
We're not used to taking care of others and we really don't want to take care of others."
Chen Zijian, 42 years old, owned a translation agency, explained it more thoroughly.
For parents with two middle-class careers, which reduce the birth rate, he said, it is to be successful enough to be selfish.
People between the ages of 20 and 30 grew up seeing their parents struggle during the first days of the Chinese experiment with capitalism and do not want that kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child takes a long time from parents, he did.
A mother has to give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are space issues, "they have to remodel their apartment", and the strategic "have to have a curriculum prepared for the best custody when the child has 9 months."
Most of your friends are willing to face this once, said Chen, but not two.
Ours is the first generation with the highest standard of living, he manifested.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
A United Nations group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN climate conference, which has so far been characterized by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, took a renewed focus on Friday with the disclosure of a document providing for ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialised nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important advance in a negotiations that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
As drafted by a UN ad hoc working group, the text does not mention how much money the rich countries would give to the poor to cope with global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their carbon production, and what would be the limit of the global increase in temperature that political strategies would be willing to tolerate.
This gives the process a lot of flexibility, said John Coequiyt, High Representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote the six-page paper, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN climate officer Yvo de Boer described as "the great panorama."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 between 25 and 45 per cent, compared with 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period between 15 and 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions between 50 per cent and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also encouraged talks on Friday, promising to provide $3,600 million annually over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday presented the same kind of verbal artificial fires that dominated the conversations last week.
The United States' special climate envoy, Todd Stern, rejected claims that require mandatory reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The manoeuvre indicated that Obama was adopting a harder line with China with respect to what the Bush administration officials had done just two years ago.
The United States will not make an agreement without the major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern said, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments one hour after China's Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said that the United States' largest climate negotiator lacked "common feeling", or was "very irresponsible" because he had said earlier this week that the United States would not economically help China to cope with global warming.
With the future economic path of the world's major power at stake, the lines of failure have erupted both within the world on the development path, as well as between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rican delegate, said it was not surprising that the main powers were discussing who should cost the costs of limiting greenhouse gases, even when vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in seeking to contain the major issuers responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change adviser in Mexico and Central America, for International Conservation.
Some of the most vulnerable countries to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants said that the talks would produce a political agreement at the very end.
The Small Island Alliance, which has 43 members, drew up a proposal for a preliminary 24-page treaty early Friday morning.
Arthur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now unified and require the action of emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency while delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues had to be resolved before the heads of government came to a close.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister, descended from the planes and ran to the corridors of the Bella Center, to meetings at closed doors and press conferences, in order to be able to limit the claims that will be raised during the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where 13,000 people come in and out of the convention center every day, the activists who touch guitar present night shows praising the countries they think are selling, and preliminary hand-to-hand proposals instead of via e-mail) poses a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all key ministers are here right now, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, Vice-President of the Global Conservation Policy.
Heavy weights are coming.
